# 11. Design Rationale

Ports establish architectural boundaries.

Without Ports, Modules frequently depend upon concrete implementations.

This increases coupling and reduces replaceability.

Aurora adopts the Port Model to ensure that capabilities remain stable even as technologies evolve.

Ports allow the platform to integrate future implementations without redesigning the architecture.

---

# 12. Future Evolution

Future versions of Aurora MAY introduce:

- Remote Ports
- Plugin Ports
- Distributed Ports
- IPC Ports
- Network Ports
- AI Provider Ports

All future Port types SHOULD remain compatible with this specification.

---

# 13. Non-Goals

A Port is NOT:

- A TypeScript interface
- A Rust trait
- A C++ abstract class
- A React hook
- An API endpoint

These are implementation mechanisms.

A Port is an architectural concept.

---

# 14. Compliance

A Port conforms to this specification when:

- It defines one capability boundary.
- It remains implementation independent.
- It exposes required behavior only.
- It enables replaceability.
- It avoids technology-specific assumptions.

---

# 15. Living Specification

The Port Model is a foundational architectural specification.

Future architectural specifications SHOULD build upon this model.

Changes SHOULD preserve compatibility whenever practical.